[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Submission from Louise Brookes[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Proposed Mass Burn Incinerator ~ Hartlebury Worcestershire [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]I write in relation to
[normal] the proposed mass burn incinerator at Hartlebury, Worcestershire which is being pursued by the two County Councils of Herefordshire and Worcestershire (with Worcestershire County Council being the lead on this proposed project). It would appear that the p
[normal]roject differs substantially from that which was presented to you previously and a full review is now necessary to ensure Value for Money and probity in public spending.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Repeated requests have been made for details of whole life costs for the proposal, to
[normal]gether with whole life costs for all other options considered. The Council are unable to provide such costs and it would therefore seem likely that they have entered into this proposal without a clearly considered and costed Options Appraisal and Business 
[normal]Case. Comparative data demonstrates that the whole life costs of this proposal are in the region of £1.5 billion and that other options are significantly less. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I would wish to draw to your attention specific points which I feel should be taken into acco
[normal]unt when considering PFI funding for this scheme. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]An urgent independent review of the Hartlebury incinerator proposal is required to review alternative approaches to waste management to ensure Value for Money. Such a review would demonstrate the major sa
[normal]vings to be made by adopting a high recycling option, including food waste collections, and by accessing the waste market. Costed Risk Assessments need to be undertaken to compare the 25 year incinerator contract versus a modular and more flexible recyclin
[normal]g option and ensure compliance with the legally binding Waste Hierarchy. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Within the attached report are the deeply held concerns that evidence the case for reviewing this lack of value for money.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The PFI Waste Management Contract includes an EfW facilit
[normal]y and has defined this to be by incineration, however it is government policy that core strategies should NOT be technology specific, therefore the PFI contract that stipulates incineration is against government policy.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is encouraging that PFI funding 
[normal]has been withdrawn for other planned incinerators that are neither needed nor cost effective. This proposal by Herefordshire and Worcestershire Councils is equally unnecessary and as such PFI funding should be refused. 
[normal]It is evident that the 25 Year PFI Wa
[normal]ste Management Contract signed in December 1998, is outdated and not fit for purpose. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I hope and trust that there is sufficient information to initiate your further investigations in the interests of the taxpayers of the two Counties.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Yours faithfully,
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Mr C Jones
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]On behalf of Herefordshire and Worcestershire Action Group
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Introduction[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Worcestershire County Council (WCC) and its’ contractor, Mercia Waste Management, are proposing to increase the waste budget at a time when waste disposal costs nationally have fallen dramatically. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The 25 year incinerator contract has failed to adequatel
[normal]y respond to, or assess Value for Money, given the substantial changes in waste policy, legislature and technology of recent years. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Council’s Review of its’ 15 year old PFI contract did not aim to find an optimum approach to waste management and has 
[normal]not considered the economic and environmental benefits of a more flexible and higher recycling option.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]INCINERATOR COSTS EXPENSIVE[bold]: Government statistics show that the average gate fee including finance and operation of a new incinerator is around £101 -1
[normal]31 per tonne 
[normal](ref 1)
[normal]. 
[normal]This is more expensive than any other waste treatment, including landfill with landfill tax. It is for this reason that ratepayers in Herefordshire and Worcestershire will have to pay at least an extra £6,000,000 (six million pounds) 
[normal]per year on top of what is already a very expensive waste contract, should the incinerator proposal proceed. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]FOOD WASTE COLLECTION CHEAPER:[bold] Half of English councils have begun separate food waste collections in the last 3 years. Food waste comprises around a third of all residual waste and can be treated more cheaply and further up the waste hierarchy by Composting or Anaerobic Digestion; bot
[normal]h of which cost around £40 per tonne. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Up to 68% of the waste to be burned could be treated for a third of the cost.
[normal] [bold]By determining to burn food waste Worcestershire County Council is risking a future legal challenge as it has a statutory duty to treat 
[normal]waste as high up the waste hierarchy as possible.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The new Waste Hierarchy has now been incorporated into 
[normal]UK
[normal] law through the Waste (
[normal]England
[normal] &amp; 
[normal]Wales
[normal]) Regulations 2011. Under this Law food waste should be identified as a waste stream and Councillors are obli
[normal]ged to apply the waste hierarchy in their approach to waste management. The proposal therefore presents a real risk to the Council.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]CLEANER RECYCLING MEANS MORE RECYLING:[bold] When organics are collected separately, the remaining other materials are much cle
[normal]aner and recycling capture rates increase. In Wales, where food waste collections are being rolled-out to all households, recycling is already 10% higher than in England (at an average of 53%) and there is a realistic target of 70% 
[normal]in the near future (some
[normal] councils are already achieving over 60% recycling). 
[normal]The separate collection of food waste allows recycling to increase and the costs to fall as the waste becomes ‘clean’. If the council funds the incinerator, the cost of increasing the rate of recycling w
[normal]ill then become so high that the level of recycling is suppressed and future targets are likely to be missed. 
[normal]This may have additional financial implications.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]LOSS OF REVENUE THANKS TO PFI FLAWS[bold]: Many Councils are paid for recyclable material at an averag
[normal]e £26 per tonne for co-mingled, and far higher prices are obtained when households separate paper, plastics, metals and glass 
[normal](ref 2)
[normal]. Unfortunately, WCC 
[normal]does not[bold] 
[normal]receive any value[bold] for their recyclate and in fact pays an 
[normal]additional recycling supplement[bold] to 
[normal]the PFI contractor of almost £6 million per annum, 
[normal]in addition to a base fee in excess of £8million per annum, which means recycling costs would be around 
[normal]£9
[normal]5 per tonne and as a result more expensive than the charge for landfilling (this could be why recyc
[normal]ling figures have stagnated for the last three years)
[normal].
[normal] This is currently a cost which ought to be a substantial saving 
[normal]of potentially £9 million per annum if both the recycling supplements and the revenue from the sale of recyclates are considered. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]MORE [bold]RISKS GOING FORWARD:[bold]  
[normal]Al
[normal]though
[normal] Worcestershire County Council’s 
[normal]PFI contract has only 10 years to run,[bold] (after which time the Council would be able to enjoy the income from recycling and be able to access the 
[normal]cheapest waste treatment alternatives [bold]available,)
[normal] they have already declared that an ‘energy from waste’ plant is the preferred option. This demonstrates a fixation with single site, single plant operation, rather than examining a more modular flexible approach. This blinkered thinking is not in the publ
[normal]ic interest and is prejudicial 
[normal]to achieving a balanced waste management process that is responsive to changing environmental, cost and legislative pressures.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The EU Waste Directive is proposing to ban the incineration of all recyclable and organic materia
[normal]l by 2020. Further, EU waste reduction levels have already been reached, meaning PFI Projects like this one are no longer needed. Such a shortfall in waste in simple terms means that there will not be enough waste to run a 200,000 tonne per year Incinerato
[normal]r during its’ 30 year life.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Council’s own reference document ( West Midlands Waste 
[normal]Al
[normal]liance Report ) clearly states that the Incinerator Bottom Ash that is not recycled is currently disposed of fairly cheaply to landfill, but there are two main threat
[normal]s to this. Firstly, it may yet be re-classified as hazardous waste under rules covering waste description. Secondly, because of this, it might also cease to be classified as inactive waste under the Landfill Tax regulations. If both of these come to pass, 
[normal]this could push the landfilling of Incinerator Bottom Ash to £100 per tonne or more, and although different contract provisions apply, it is nevertheless the Authorities who have contracted for the EfW Plants who will largely bear the financial burden.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Al
[normal]l household waste, whether for recycling or ‘residual’, collected by Herefordshire and Worcestershire is given to the PFI contractor, Mercia, to process at an overall cost currently o
[normal]f £39.5m p/a 
[normal](graph 1)
[normal] – or around £106 per tonne for all 370,000 tonnes. This does not include the cost of collecting waste, which is paid for separately, and is not part of this PFI contract.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]                
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]               Graph 1: H&amp;[bold]W PFI Contract : Annual Unitary Charge paid to the Contractor.[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]In order to benefit from the dramatically cheaper and greener alternatives to incineration and landfill, waste needs to be collected and treated in three streams; recyclables, organics (food and garden waste) and residuals. This will require WCC to adopt a
[normal] more modern co-ordinated approach to waste management and to work more closely with the Districts who collect the waste in order to achieve the best overall costs and benefits. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The contractors have only been able to persuade the Council that incineratio
[normal]n is the cheapest option because they only quote future landfill costs for comparison and overall incinerator contract costs are kept secret. Using the WRAP Gate Fees Report 
[normal](ref 1)
[normal] to overcome commercial confidentiality, cost comparisons per tonne for the
[normal] alternative treatment processes are clearly shown 
[normal](graph 2)
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]                       
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]                    
[normal]Graph 2: showing the Cost of waste treatment options per tonne [bold](see ref 1)[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]WCC have argued that extra collection costs will make the higher recycling alternative too expensive. This is not the case. As a recent Eunomia Report 
[normal](ref 2)
[normal] has shown, the cost of collecting mixed recyclables is the same as collecting residual waste. 
[normal]So 
[normal]the huge savings would be of great financial benefit and more than off-set any additional cost of food waste collection.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]A 25 year incinerator contract is a massive commercial undertaking with overall costs including fin
[normal]ance and operation of around 
[normal]£1.5 billion.
[normal] Yet there seems little evidence that WCC have undertaken the necessary Risk Assessment crucial to ensuring long-term economic viability. This would need to be a central issue for the Review. Below is a sample of t
[normal]he risks taken from WCC’s own ‘Risk Register’ 
[normal](ref 4)
[normal]:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]‘Affordability’[bold] is seen as the top risk due to increased recycling, new Waste and Health Legislation and competition from the expanding waste market. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]‘[bold]Recycling’[bold] is another risk for the council in that if
[normal] 
[normal]''the councils significantly increase their recycling targets
[normal]", it could result in,
[normal] "Additional cost to councils''. The contract is based on a recycling rate of just 42% and any increases to this rate will mean s
[normal]pare incinerator capacity will also increase. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The contract would guarantee payments until 2023 for an amount which would average out at £130 per tonne, if the Council used all 200,000 tonnes capacity per year. However the increasing s
[normal]pare capacity envisaged would mean that the effective price per tonne would increase beyond this cost. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]WCC have said that C&amp;I waste will be available to buy the spare space but this is highly unlikely given that almost all C&amp;I waste is recyclable or can 
[normal]be processed for a fraction of the WCC gate/contract fee. The Council will then face subsidising outside waste by lowering their gate fee.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]John Hobbs, Director of Environmental Services at Worcestershire Council, has recently stated that the waste budget is going to cost an additional £6,000,000 (6 million pounds) per year if the proposal for the incinerator goes ahead, and that this would co
[normal]me from other budgets. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This raises the question of precisely how this will be funded and what affect this will have on other services?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]This reinforces the need to undertake full and current costings
[normal] of all available alternatives and such sequential testing as is necessary to demonstrate financial probity. Indeed, such investigation may very well identify a cheaper alternative and this fact should not be ignored.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is extremely con
[normal]cerning that the Council are proposing to guarantee profits for Mercia Waste using taxpayers money with their statement 
[normal]“Mercia Waste Management will get an agreed return on their investment which they state is currently scheduled to end in 2023”.
[normal] Favourin
[normal]g the contractor in this way contravenes EU Procurement Law.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Government policy seems to indicate that Core Strategies should not be technology specific.
[normal] However, the Waste Management Contract drawn up in 1998 clearly states 
[normal]that the Waste to Energy Plant means Waste Incinerator and therefore the strategy embodied in the contract is patently and seriously in conflict with current policy and should
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]be rewritten
[normal]. In fact, there is a clause in the Contract stating: 
[normal]" Voluntary Te
[normal]rmination by the Councils " - which may be called upon after ten years from the contracts effective start date, if it can be shown there exists ”new technology providing significant cost savings“.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This clause was never utilised - raising the question ‘why’
[normal]?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Environmental Legislation and Policy:[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Councils are legally required to follow the Waste Hierarchy - treating waste by prevention, re-use and recycling before burning. Worcestershire County Council, in failing to provide a fully costed options 
[normal]appraisal have failed to seriously consider any waste treatment option that moves waste further up the Hierarchy. Consequently, the residual waste treatment by the two counties is likely to remain rooted to the bottom of the waste Hierarchy until 2023, and
[normal] for the life of the proposed incinerator.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Waste Hierarchy will be further strengthened by forthcoming legislation. For example, the EU has resolved to ban both plastics and organics from incineration.   
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]     
[normal]         Chart 1: Fossil CO[bold]2[bold] Emissions[bold] from Electricity Generation, and the 2030 Target.[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Energy Production Risks:[bold]&#xa0;[bold]The proposed Incinerator will produce around 200,000 tonnes of CO
[normal]2
[normal] a year along with other dangerous pollutants. The likelihood is that incinerators will soon be liable for carbon or incineration taxes. This was indicated in the Waste Review of 2011 and will not reach carbon budgets set by the Committee on Climate Change
[normal] for energy production by 2030 
[normal](Chart 1)
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]This extra tax will be borne by local taxpayers.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In contrast, Anaerobic Digestion produces near carbon-free energy and its’ residue is a useful fertiliser. The Government has stated its preference for Anaerobic 
[normal]Digestion over Incineration for dealing with certain waste and has placed it higher up the legally-binding Waste Hierarchy.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The PFI contract will end in 10 years time, but the proposed incine
[normal]rator would have a life of 25 to 30 years. At contract-end, Mercia Waste Management will no longer be obliged to run the plant. Despite this the Council must agree to pay for the outstanding finance; the ‘balloon payment’ to the banks. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Cabinet papers
[normal] state, ‘
[normal]There is a risk that at that point Mercia are not good for the money and 
[normal]the Councils are left overpaying for a 'broken' plant’ 
[normal](ref 5)
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The European Procurement Office have stated that such a ‘
[normal]balloon payment’ would be in[bold] 
[normal]contravention of European Law [bold]and that action would be taken following such a breach resulting in even more unnecessary costs being burdened on the taxpayer. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Any extension of the existing contract to beyond 2023 is likely to harm the 
[normal]taxpayer in a number
[normal] of ways:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]If 
[normal]Mercia
[normal] is no longer ‘
[normal]good for the money’ 
[normal]and decide not to tender in 2023, it will send a clear message to other competing contractors that the ageing incinerator is not a good proposition. WCC will be in a very we
[normal]ak bargaining position and at best it will have to increase contract payments or at worst face paying for a white elephant. It certainly entails, ‘
[normal]unpredictable costs in the future’
[normal] 
[normal](ref 5)
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Council are taking on commercial risks, notably lack of future feedstock and forthcoming Environmental Legislation, which the contractor would not accept and which would have been too expensive to insure against. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The acceptance by the Council of thes
[normal]e risks may result in a mismatch of the interests of WCC and the contractor, Mercia, and this should be scrutinised to avoid the contravention of the legally enforceable public procurement rule, ‘
[normal]a change in the risk/reward share in the original contract’
[normal].
[normal](ref 5.19b)
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Mercia[bold] developed the incinerator proposal and fought for the 25 year proposal at the Public Inquiry. However they have not had to consider the need for flexible waste disposal which complies with the new Waste Hierarchy or take into account t[bold]he substantial changes taking place in waste policy, management practices or the development of a highly competitive waste market, [bold]because those risks have been accepted by the Council[bold].[bold] They have not had to consider the overall cost envelope in the context
[normal] of the current and future budgets, or in the context of the new austerity, because affordability is the Council’s risk.
[normal]These risks were not present at the time of the original contract and they are specific to a long-term inflexible contract for rigid in
[normal]frastructure in the changed risk profile detailed above. These risks 
[normal]constitute a ‘
[normal]a change in the risk/reward share in the original contract’
[normal].
[normal](ref 5 19b)
[normal] which necessitates urgent scrutiny before the project progresses further.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Cabinet papers for 13
[normal]t
[normal]h
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Dec 2012 states that they have sought assurances from the Treasury regarding payment of the 'Balloon Payment' ( potentially many 100s of £millions? ) and in the 'Financial Parameters' state, '
[normal]following dialogue with HM Treasury an infrastructure guarante
[normal]e could be made available to
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Project
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]financiers for any balloon payments, if required
[normal].' The Council and Treasury may create a serious ‘moral hazard’ for Mercia by such a perceived state guarantee as it may remove the incentive to carry out
[normal] proper operation
[normal] and maintenance of the incinerator for its’ 25-30 year life, 15 of which may be after Mercia’s contract ends. Motivation for the private enterprise to be competitive or act in the public interest is reduced when the most profitable aspect of the PFI – its
[normal]’ financing – appears guaranteed. This could impact on the effective running of the plant, including the potential for emission breaches later in the plant's life. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Costed Risk Assessments need to be undertaken to compare the 25 year incinerator contract 
[normal]versus a modular and more flexible recycling option and ensure compliance with the legally binding Waste Hierarchy in order to protect future Council finances.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Worcestershire County Council have repeatedly failed to provide a f
[normal]ull Business Case 
[normal]detailing CAPEX ,OPEX or lifecycle costs, to members of the public for this proposal
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Worcestershire County Council cannot provide an 
[normal]Options Appraisal that has been fully costed and so it would appear that no alternatives have been pro
[normal]perly and intelligently considered.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is of deep concern 
[normal]that the Council are unable to provide evidence that they have investigated all options fully, something which is surely essential in order to demonstrate Best Value?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]To date, they have refused 
[normal]to produce whole life budget costs for all options and have clearly only compared the costs of incineration against landfill. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Of similar concern is the fact that 
[normal]DEFRA  has no copy of either the Business Case or the Contract in spite of clearly stating i
[normal]n guidance, that it is in the public interest for these to be made available.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The 
[normal]Council
[normal] 
[normal]now recognise that there is no host for the heat element 
[normal]due to the rural location
[normal] 
[normal](
[normal]something that the Council accept as being detrimental to the perceived benefits of the plant) 
[normal]and no likelihood in the foreseeable future. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is believed that failure to utilise the heat will result in lost revenue of over £100 million over 25 years[bold]. [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Furthermore, regarding the power element, the Council have stated that the facility would need to provide value for money without electricity generation
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Plans presented to the planning inquiry detailing how it will connect to the National Grid have now be
[normal]en revoked. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Worcestershire[bold] [bold]County[bold] Council is now unable to explain how the electricity will be utilised or connected.[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]This should bring into question the whole viability of the proposal as significant revenue, and surely the rationale for selecting this
[normal] option, will be lost. This also raises the question of whether the location of the site was ever suitable, and the whole site selection process is therefore so obviously flawed.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Landfill:[bold] In addition to the fact that heat cannot be u
[normal]tilised, it is also pertinent to highlight that the site itself is within an area of existing landfills. It is well documented that these landfills produce significant amounts of landfill gas, which is known to migrate some distance, 
[normal]requiring additional a
[normal]nd unnecessary costs to mitigate such risks. 
[normal]Due diligence in this regard was not demonstrated at the time of land purchase
[normal] 
[normal]as these risks are a real hazard.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Water Supply:[bold] The location of the site also necessitates other significant costs as there is no natural water supply, and as such new infrastructure will be required. The considerable water needs of the Plant, in excess of 46 million litres per year, will have to be me
[normal]t from the public water supply.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Wildlife:[bold] The ongoing costs of wildlife removal (including Great Crested Newts) are significant. This had also not been properly considered at the time of purchase and again demonstrates the total lack of due diligence.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Green Belt:[bold] Siting the proposed incinerator in the Green Belt also necessitates lowering the plant into the ground by over 8 metres. This is a significant additional cost as is the cost of land drainage and the need to divert a stream which runs through th
[normal]e centre of the site. This demonstrates the unsuitability of the site, lack of due diligence and significant, unnecessary costs.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Land Cost:[bold] It is important to note that the Council purchased the site at a cost of approximately £4.5 million in 2007 (aft
[normal]er the decision not to locate an autoclave on the site) without undertaking sufficient and proper checks
[normal]. The site is next to a problematic landfill and the land is well-documented to be contaminated.
[normal] The Council claim that the value paid was ‘comparable t
[normal]o other sites’ but it is not clear that this claim can be sufficiently evidenced. Especially, as later the same year, it seems that Worcestershire County Council purchased a similar site in a prime location for approximately £1.5 million less. This raises 
[normal]a host of questions about the council’s procurement procedures that are worthy of further investigation. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]There is no comprehensive transport plan or route plan available and therefore no associated 
[normal]costs
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]available. This is of course a significant element of cost given the vast distances that the waste would need to travel due to the non-central and rural location of the proposed plant.
[normal] 
[normal]No environmental benefit
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]can be demonstrated.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]There are currently five operational incinerators within the 
[normal]West Midlands
[normal] area, all of which are reported to be running at levels of under-capacity, thus bringing into question the economic viability of
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]this
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]project. This level of spare capacity
[normal] will further increase when the two incinerators currently under construction ( Four Ashes, and Battlefield ) begin operation in 2015. This lack of need is compounded by the fact that waste levels are still falling, 
[normal]highlighting
[normal] that there is no demonstrab
[normal]le need for this scheme, and its sustainability is questionable.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Detailed below is a graph 
[normal](graph 3)
[normal] showing that waste levels locally have fallen by over 48,000 tonnes since 2006. Whilst recycling has increased nationally with some councils already achieving over 60%, in Herefordshire and Worcestershire recycling has only increased by little more than 1
[normal],000 tonnes in the last 3 years. This equates to an increase of just 1% per year.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]                   
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]  
[normal]Graph 3: How H&amp;W has treated or disposed of its’ waste, (amounts shown in tonnes).[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The graph 
[normal](Graph 4) 
[normal]below,
[normal] 
[normal]shows the wide disparity in recycling 
[normal]levels reached so far by each individual Council within the partnership, some of whom have barely reached 30%.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]                                
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]                        
[normal]Graph 4: Local recycling rates – some barely reaching 30%[bold]              [bold]              [bold]          [bold]              [bold]   The average[bold] rate for the whole of [bold]England[bold] is 43%.[bold]  [bold]              [bold]   The Highest rate in England (Vale of White Horse) is 68%[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The Government is now acknowledging that there is overcapacity by removing PFI credits from both the 
[normal]Al
[normal]lerton
[normal] 
[normal]Park
[normal] proposal in 
[normal]Yorkshire
[normal] and in Merseyside. Both of these projects were set to cost over £1 billion and are therefore comparable in many ways to the proposal by this Council 
[normal](graph 5)
[normal].
[normal]It is worth noting that the cumulative costs shown below in the graph, are for the costs for th
[normal]e service currently provided, and do not include any of the increases that will come from the financing, constructing and running of the proposed incinerator. 
[normal]An overall cost in excess of £1 billion is likely.
[normal]&#xa0;
