[normal]References:
[normal]No government support for Allerton Park incinerator
[normal] ~ 
[normal]http://www.bbc.co.uk/news
[normal]/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-21537662
[normal]Government pulls £90m Mersey incinerator funding
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]~ 
[normal]http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/liverpool-ne
[normal]ws/local-news/2013/02/25/government-pulls-90m-mersey-incinerator-funding-100252-32873347/
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Within both these reports is a clear statement that the Government pulled out of these projects as ‘there are already enough incinerators in England to meet tight E
[normal]U deadlines to reduce landfill’.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As has just been demonstrated by the withdrawal of funding for the PFI incinerators in York and Merseyside
[normal], 
[normal]the Government is fully aware of the fact that there is an overcapacity of incinerators. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The 
[normal]West Midlands
[normal], which encompasses Herefordshire and Worcestershire, has met all its landfill diversion targets 5 years early and is almost at 2020 target levels. As a region it burns more waste than any other, and waste levels continue to fall. One local landfill, which
[normal] opened in 2010, may soon be mothballed due to a lack of waste, although it was meant to be operational until 2020 at least. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It must therefore be assumed that there is even more reason to halt this scheme than those areas who have already had funding wit
[normal]hdrawn. Furthermore, the report by Eunomia Research 
[normal](ref 6)
[normal] highlights this overcapacity. This report found that there is a 
[normal]considerable overcapacity
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]even before this proposed incinerator is ever built. This is evidenced in the chart below, based on that r
[normal]esearch:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]                       
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]  
[normal] Chart 2: Incineration capacity in the West Midlands outstrips the amount of waste [bold](ref 6)[bold]It would be considered grossly negligent for this project to be allowed to proceed without forensic financial scrutiny. Cheaper
[normal] options are available, and with such a high long-term risk to the public purse in times of austerity, it is absolutely vital that these alternatives are used over the costly option of incineration.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]WCC’s contract with 
[normal]Mercia
[normal] began in 1998 and has only 10 more years to run. After this, WCC will be free to tender out its waste streams in the open waste market at the lower gate/contract costs and also gain the benefit of recyclate sales. Th
[normal]e Council has a number of alternatives to start the move towards cheaper, modular and more flexible waste treatment technologies during this period.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Council’s Cabinet Meeting of 
[normal]February 2013 
[normal]states that it is technically possible to recycle most of i
[normal]ts’ waste but this, it claims, would be too costly. 
[normal]As detailed in this report, recycling provides an income for Councils, or can be treated for a fraction of the cost of incineration. The Council statement confirms the extremely high costs of recycling in
[normal] the present contract and could suggest that the present PFI Contract is weighted toward the Contractor. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]How to Save £20million a year:[bold]Recently  Eunomia Research produced a Report for a Council considering a similar sized incinerator
[normal](ref 2)
[normal]. It gives 
[normal]cost comparisons taking into account changing waste management systems and accessing the open waste market. Instead of a 240,000 tonne incinerator, they estimate that
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]£[bold]2[bold]0 million p.y. would be saved[bold]&#xa0;[bold]by simply diverting recyclable materials out of the PFI 
[normal]contract and onto the open market. By getting out of the contract altogether
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]£20 million per year can be saved[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Al
[normal]so Government policy currently is to renegotiate old PFI Contracts to produce savings for Councils and it may be possible that local MPs may 
[normal]be able to help with this during the remaining 10 years of the Mercia Waste PFI. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The most efficient way to remove organics from landfill and avoid landfill tax is by either building Anaerobic Digestion plants or by accessing the existing well-established
[normal] AD market. To build 2 AD Plant to process 40,000 tonnes of food waste would cost around £10 million 
[normal]to £15 million, an amount easily offset by the reduction in landfill tax liability that would result.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]If the Council still considers there is a need for 
[normal]incineration in the medium term, then tendering the waste to the other West Midlands incinerators should be considered first as there is spare capacity already in most of these, and a national overcapacity of incineration due by 2015 
[normal](ref 6)
[normal]. The gate fees
[normal] of older incinerators are also lower than the contract fees for newly-built facilities.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]If the Council still considers it needs its own infrastructure then a far smaller plant for truly residual waste would cost less, allow for greater flexibility and ac
[normal]cess to the highly competitive waste market. However, before this decision can be made it will be necessary to review Herefordshire and Worcestershire’s approach to waste management and the savings that could be made by adopting a high-recycling option.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]* 
[normal]Al
[normal]l attempts have been made to ensure that the figures and information used in this report are accurate. However as WCC have refused to disclose key information, reliance has been placed on the Government’s own statistics to aim at overcoming commercial 
[normal]confidentiality.
